Attributes:

  • id: Unique identifier for each entry
  • c_date: Date of the campaign

  • category: Category of the campaign (e.g., social, search, influencer, media)

  • mark_spent: Amount spent on the campaign
  • clicks: Number of clicks received
  • leads: Number of leads generated
  • orders: Number of orders made
  • revenue: Revenue generated from the campaign

# Write function to detect outliers

def detect_outliers(df, column):
    Q1 = df[column].quantile(0.25) # Calculate 25th percentile
    Q3 = df[column].quantile(0.75) # Calculate 75th percentile
    IQR = Q3 - Q1 # Calculate IQR
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR # Define lower bound
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR # Define upper bound
    outliers = df[(df[column] < lower_bound) | (df[column] > upper_bound)] # Find outliers
    
    # Print the results
    print(f"Outliers detected in '{column}':")
    print(outliers[column])
    print(f"Number of outliers: {outliers.shape[0]}")
    print(f"Lower bound: {lower_bound}; Upper bound: {upper_bound}")

# Write function to visualise ouliers

def visualise_outliers(df, columns):
    num_rows = (len(columns) + 1) // 2 # Ensure that the last row will display a plot even if the number of plots is odd
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(num_rows, 2, figsize=(15, 5*num_rows)) # Plot displaying 2 plots on each row
    axes = axes.flatten() # Convert the axes array (which is a 2D array when there are multiple rows and columns of subplots) into a 1D array

    # If there is only 1 plot, then I need to convert it into a list so that I can use it in the same way as when there are multiple subplots
    if len(columns) == 1:
        axes = [axes]

    # Plot boxplots
    for i, column in enumerate(columns):
        sns.boxplot(x=df[column], ax=axes[i])
        axes[i].set_title(f"Boxplot of {column.capitalize()}")

        # Turn off unused axes to avoid displaying empty plots
        for j in range (len(columns), len(axes)):
            axes[j].axis('off')
            
    plt.tight_layout(pad=2)
    plt.show()

# Write function to plot key metrics

def plot_key_metrics(df, key_metrics):
    num_rows = (len(key_metrics) + 1) // 2 # Ensure that the last row will display a plot even if the number of plots is odd
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(num_rows, 2, figsize=(15, 5*num_rows)) # Plot displaying 2 plots on each row
    axes = axes.flatten() # Convert the axes array (which is a 2D array when there are multiple rows and columns of subplots) into a 1D array

    # If there is only 1 plot, then I need to convert it into a list so that I can use it in the same way as when there are multiple subplots
    if len(key_metrics) == 1:
        axes = [axes]

    # Plot boxplots
    for i, key_metric in enumerate(key_metrics):
        sns.histplot(x=df[key_metric], bins=30, kde=True, ax=axes[i])
        axes[i].set_title(f"Boxplot of {key_metric.capitalize()}")
        axes[i].set_xlabel(f"{key_metric.capitalize()}")

    # Turn off unused axes to avoid displaying empty plots
    for j in range (len(key_metrics), len(axes)):
        axes[j].axis('off')
            
    plt.tight_layout(pad=2)
    plt.show()

# Calculate original value
def find_original_value(log1p_value):
    original_value = np.expm1(log1p_value)
    print(f"Original value is: {original_value}")

# Calculate log1p value
def find_log1p_value(original_value):
    log1p_value = np.log1p(original_value)
    print(f"Log1p value is: {log1p_value}")

2. Feature Engineering

Comments

To improve the analysis, I will create additional marketing metrics, such as:

  1. ROMI helps measure the effectiveness of marketing campaigns by showing how much revenue is generated for every dollar spent on marketing.
$$ \text{ROMI (Return on Marketing Investment)} = \frac{\text{Revenue} - \text{Marketing Spend}}{\text{Marketing Spend}} \times 100 $$
  1. CTR measures how often people click on an ad or link after seeing it.
$$ \text{CTR (Click-Through Rate)} = \frac{\text{Total Number of Clicks}}{\text{Total Number of Impressions}} \times 100 $$
  1. Conversion Rate shows how effective the website (or landing page) is at converting clicks into actual actions (e.g., sales)
$$ \text{Conversion Rate} = \frac{\text{Total Number of Conversions (e.g., Orders)}}{\text{Total Number of Clicks}} \times 100 $$
  1. AOV measures the average revenue generated per order.
$$ \text{AOV (Average Order Value)} = \frac{\text{Total Revenue}}{\text{Total Number of Orders}} $$

# Calculate ROMI for categories and campaigns

# For categories
categories_romi = df.groupby('category', observed=True).agg(
    total_revenue=('revenue', 'sum'),
    total_marketing_spend=('marketing_spend', 'sum')
).reset_index()
categories_romi['romi'] = ((categories_romi['total_revenue'] - categories_romi['total_marketing_spend']) /
                           (categories_romi['total_marketing_spend']) * 100)

df.rename(columns={'romi': 'categories_romi'}, inplace=True)

# For campaigns

    total_revenue = ('revenue', 'sum'),
    total_marketing_spend=('marketing_spend', 'sum')
).reset_index()
campaigns_romi['romi'] = ((campaigns_romi['total_revenue'] - campaigns_romi['total_marketing_spend']) / 
                          (campaigns_romi['total_marketing_spend']) * 100)
df = df.merge(campaigns_romi[['campaign_name', 'romi']], on='campaign_name', how='left')
df.rename(columns={'romi': 'campaigns_romi'}, inplace=True)

3. Bulding Machine Learning Model to Predict the Number of Orders

3.1. Handle Outliers

Since the analysis is done, I will handle outliers using Z-scores to achieve a better performance of a machine learning model.

In[563]:
# Calculate Z-scores for numerical features
numerical_columns = ['impressions', 'marketing_spend', 'clicks', 'leads', 'orders', 'revenue', 'categories_romi', 
                     'campaigns_romi', 'categories_ctr', 'campaigns_ctr', 'categories_cr', 'campaigns_cr', 'categories_aov', 'campaigns_aov']
z_scores = np.abs(stats.zscore(df[numerical_columns]))

# Define a threshold of 3 for Z-scores
outlier_threshold = 3
df_clean = df[(z_scores < outlier_threshold).all(axis=1)]

# Check how many outliers were removed
print(f"Removed {len(df) - len(df_clean)} outliers")

Removed 19 outliers

Comments

Search Category is performing very well, but others models can be improved. I will focus on tuning hyperparameters. Hyperparameter tuning is the process of finding the best combination of hyperparameters that optimizes model performance.

I will use RandomizedSearchCV, which:

  • Randomly searches across a specified range of hyperparameters.
  • Evaluates different combinations using cross-validation.
  • Returns the best combination of hyperparameters based on a scoring metric (e.g., MSE, R).

3.8.1. Tuning Hyperparameters (All Categories Model)

In[608]:
# Define the hyperparameter space for RandomizedSearchCV
param_dist = {
    'n_estimators': randint(100, 1000),        # Number of trees in the forest
    'max_depth': randint(1, 20),               # Max depth of each tree
    'min_samples_split': randint(2, 20),       # Minimum samples required to split a node
    'min_samples_leaf': randint(1, 20),        # Minimum samples required to be a leaf
    'max_features': ['sqrt', 'log2', None]     # Number of features to consider for splitting
}

# Initialise random forest regressor
rf_model_best = RandomForestRegressor(random_state=42)

# Set up RandomizedSearchCV
random_search = RandomizedSearchCV(
    rf_model_best,          # RandomForestRegressor model
    param_distributions=param_dist,       # Hyperparameter space defined earlier
    n_iter=100,        # Number of random combinations of hyperparameters to test
    cv=5,              # Number of cross-validation folds to evaluate each combination
    verbose=1,         # Verbosity level
    n_jobs=-1,         # Use all available CPU cores to speed up training
    random_state=42    # For reproducibility
)

# Fit the model with RandomizedSearchCV and search for the best parameters
random_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Access the best model from the search
rf_model_best = random_search.best_estimator_

# Output the best hyperparameters
print(f"Best parameters found (All Categories) are: {random_search.best_params_}")

# Predict using the best model
y_pred = random_search.best_estimator_.predict(X_test)

# Calculate MSE and R-squared
mse_best = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
r2_best = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)

# Perform cross-validation with the best model to evaluate generalization
cross_val_scores_best = cross_val_score(random_search.best_estimator_, X_train, y_train, cv=5, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')

Fitting 5 folds for each of 100 candidates, totalling 500 fits
Best parameters found (All Categories) are: {'max_depth': 5, 'max_features': 'sqrt', 'min_samples_leaf': 1, 'min_samples_split': 3, 'n_estimators': 152}

After tuning, MSE and R-squared improved; however, cross-validation MSE became worse. To fix this, I will try to increase the number of folds to get a more representative estimate of performance.

In my opinion, this is due to the fact that the data set is not large enough: splitting the data into folds for cross-validation leaves even smaller subsets for training and testing; this increases the variability of the model's performance across folds, making the cross-validation metric less stable and often worse after tuning.

4. Conclusion

4.1. Understanding the Data Set

  • The data set is small with only 308 rows and 11 columns. The data set includes information about how different categories and campaigns performed during 1 month (February 2021). The performance indicators are: impressions, marketing spend, clicks, leads, orders, revenue.
  • Firstly, I checked the descriptive statistics as well as checked for missing values and incorrect data types. There was no missing values; I changed the data types where it was needed; the data set looked well-organised and ready to be analysed.
  • Then, I identified and visualised outliers (using boxplots). All key metrics columns had outliers ranging from 22 to 39 per column. The 'impressions' column had the most extreme outliers with values in the order of magnitude of 10^7 to 10^8. Since I could not determine if outliers were valid data points (rare but significant) or errors, I decided not to remove or modify them until the building of machine learning models stage.

4.2. Statistical Analysis and Data Visualisation

  • At this stage, I moved to analysing the data set by creating data visualisations to find patterns and insights.
  • Firstly, I visualised revenue and marketing spend over time and found out that: in the beginning of February, the values were average, then they fell, then there was a spike (a more significant one for marketing spend), and then again the fall, resulting in very low numbers closer to the end of February. I would recommend to see what had caused the spike, because it would help to understand what needs to be done to keep the revenue higher.
  • Secondly, I plotted histograms of the key metrics, which were highly right-skewed, with a significant number of low and zero values; that is why the distribution of higher values was difficult to read. To fix this, I created new columns doing log transformation of the key metrics and plotted them. I found out that there are many values of revenue = 0, while there are no values of marketing spend = 0, meaning that each campaign had some money invested in it even if such a campaign did not make any revenue. There were many values of impressions = about 442412.4. The clicks histogram was left-skewed, meaning that each campaign attracted a significant number of clicks. The leads histogram was less left-skewed than the Clicks Plot; however, still the number of leads was usually higher. Very often only 1 order was made and less often (but still often) about 4 orders were made.
  • Then, I moved to analysing how the revenue and marketing spend differ across different categories and campaigns. Based on the revenue, the influencer category was the most successful one with the sum of revenue of almost 200,000 and the marketing spend of 75,000 (which was not the highest one and was significantly smaller than the revenue made). The youtube_blogger campaign was the most successful one with the sum of revenue being 140,000 - that is 2.3 times higher than the next successful campaign's revenue, which is a significant difference. The marketing spend on this campaign was slightly less than 40,000 - which is 3.5 times less than the revenue - again, a significant difference, proving that this campaign was extremely successful. The least successful campaign was facebook_lal, which made a revenue of about 5,000 only, and the marketing spend was about 25,000 - which shows, that the marketing spend was 5 times higher than the revenue - a significant difference, proving that this campaign was the least successful one.
  • After that, I moved to analysing how the key metrics (impressions, clicks, orders, leads) differ across different categories and campaigns; and since the distribution of values of key metrics was too large, I visualised log transformed version of these metrics. The plot showed that the sum of impressions compared to other values was significantly larger - the next variable is clicks, then leads, and the smallest one is orders. I sorted the barplots to show the highest number of orders; and (with an exception of a few campaigns' impressions and clicks) all other key metrics followed the same distribution - meaning that for the highest number of orders, there was the highest number of impressions, clicks, and leads. The highest number of all key metrics was achieved by the social category. The highest number of orders was achieved by the youtube_blogger campaign. However, the highest number of impressions was achieved by banner_partner (this campaign achieved the second highest number of orders). The highest number of clicks and the second highest number of impressions was achieved by instagram_tier2; however, this campaign achieved only the second lowest number of orders.
  • Plotting a correlation matrix of all key metrics showed that there was a weak / almost no correlation between impressions and other metrics (<= 0.25). However, all other metrics had a moderate to strong correlation. The strongest correlation was between revenue and orders (which makes sense since the more orders, the higher the revenue) and between orders and marketing spend (which shows that the more money is invested in marketing, the more orders it generates). However, it is interesting that the correlation between revenue and marketing spend was significantly lower (0.76).

4.3. Feature Engineering

  • To improve the analysis, I created additional marketing metrics, such as: ROMI (Return on Marketing Investment), CTR (Click-Through Rate), Conversion Rate, and AOV (Average Order Value).
  • The highest return on marketing investment by category was about 150 (influencer) and the lowest one was about -10 (social - the only negative one). The highest return on marketing investment by campaign was about 225 (youtube_blogger) and the lowest one was about -75 (facebook_lal). In total, there were 5 campaigns with negative return on marketing investment: (lowest to highest) facebook_lal, instagram_tier2, google_wide, facebOOK_tier2, facebook_tier1.
  • The highest click-through rate by category was about 0.95 (influencer) and the lowest one was about 0.05 (media). The highest click-through rate by campaign was about 3.0 (facebook_retargeting) and the lowest one was about 0.1 (banner_partner).
  • The highest conversion rate by category was 0.4 (influencer) and the lowest one was 0.17 (social). The highest conversion rate by campaign was 0.41 (youtube_blogger) and the lowest one was 0.06 (instagram_tier2).
  • The highest AOV by category was 62 (influencer) and the lowest one was 40 (media). The highest AOV by campaign was 72 (youtube_blogger) and the lowest one was 10 (facebook_lal).

4.4. Building Machine Learning Models

  • After the analysis, I moved to building machine learning models to predict the number of orders. I handled outliers using Z-scores to achieve a better performance of machine learning models and performed label encoding.
  • I chose to build random forest models for all categories and then for individual categories because some categories' performance significantly differed for the others'.
  • After building and analysing the performance of initial models, I decided to improve them by performing hyperparameters tuning.
  • After building all the models, I plotted Feature Importances for each model. All models had CTR by category as the least important feature. Search and Influencer Models had leads as the most important feature; while all other models had marketing spend as the most important feature.
  • The most successful model was the All Categories Model after tuning (MSE=39.40, R2=0.98), because it significantly improved after tuning and it can predict the number of orders for all categories.
  • I have also built models for each category and achieved very good results for Influencer Model after tuning (MSE=39.40, R2=0.98) and Search Model before tuning (MSE=5.47, R2=0.96). However, the other 2 models for Media and Social Categories performed worse (although, not too bad). In my opinion, this is due to the data set being small.
  • Cross-Validated MSEs became worse after tuning for all models. However, the Search Model had the lowest Cross-Validated MSE before tuning (CV MSE=29.99).
  • Despite that the Search Model had better performance scores, I would recommend to use the All Categories Model, beacause it still performed well and I had more data to train it. If the data set was larger, then building individual models would make more sense.
